text: Everyone is complaining about the CGI.¬† In the 60s and 70s, the Japanese filmmakers relied on scale models for WW2 movies.¬† You could easily tell the planes were models but it was for some reason really fun to watch.¬† The scale models could even simulate machine gun and cannon fire from the wings and fuselage.¬† An American war movie made in the 60s about a DC-10 transport plane full of Marines being shot down on a remote Pacific island containing a small Japanese garrison used the Japanese model techniques to depict the DC-10 being shot down by a Japanese zero.¬† The zero and an escorting Marine F-4U Corsair shoot each other down.¬† The best fighter plane movie, however, is the British, BATTLE OF BRITAIN, hands down.¬† Besides using actual surviving WW2 airplanes, the Brits used flying scale models and forced perspective to depict British Hurricanes and Spitfires and German Bf-109s and Heinkel bombers.¬† After that, the 1977 movie, MIDWAY does a fairly good job but a lot of the flying scenes utilize a prop cockpit with the actor sitting in it and the camera just showing the cockpit.
author: Grande Artiste

text: The Battle of Midway was the combination of Stalingrad and Kursk set on the water for the Japanese.¬† The offensive momentum of the Japanese advance halted for good and from then on the Japanese were on the strategic defensive.¬† The Japanese Navy still remained powerful though, as shown by two, Japanese¬†naval victories in the Solomon Islands during the Guadalcanal campaign, relying on traditional surface ship-to-ship duels.¬† But those resulted in just tactical victories.¬† The Americans could not be pushed back and were able to replace their losses easily from late 1943 onwards.¬† Without their full, pre-war carrier strength and experienced naval carrier pilots, the Japanese could not regain the offensive.
author: Grande Artiste

text: Who cares about those comments about CGI. This movie will be awesome so sit back enjoy the movie.
author: John Tad

text: The death of something like 240 Japanese carrier pilots¬†stranded on their burning carriers during the Battle of Midway¬†may have saved the lives of hundreds if not thousands of Allied fighter and bomber pilots, and possible Allied ground forces in the next 24 months of grueling, grinding combat in the Pacific.¬† Those 240 plus Japanese carrier pilots were literally worth their weight in gold. While everyone in wartime must be replaceable and expendable, those men were not.¬† Japanese pre-war pilot naval training was exceptionally intensive and described as brutal.¬† The strongest and the fittest survived and then went on to earn years of practical battle experience flying the wartime skies over China in the late 30s.¬† In other words, it took years to create a fully trained, completely experienced Japanese naval aviator.¬† The Japanese did not have that luxury once war broke out with America on December 7, 1941.¬† Those who read WW2 military history in the Pacific are astonished at the number of victories the experienced Japanese naval and army fighter pilots racked up in the first six months of war.¬† The Japanese shot down inexperienced Allied pilots here and there. Cut-throat battle attrition wore down the Japanese fighter pilot ranks and the Japanese could not replace those men with replacements of equal quality.¬† Meanwhile the Americans and British were able to organize well-designed fighter training programs at a multitude of training schools.¬† By late 1944, air combat against the Japanese was beginning to resemble a slaughter.¬† The inexperienced and not fully trained Japanese naval and army pilots could not cope.¬† It took all their efforts to focus on flying their machines.¬† The Allies still had to be careful because Japan still retained a number of surviving experienced fighter pilots, 'honchos', but even the ranks of these men fell to attrition.¬† By the beginning of 1945, only experienced Japanese fighter pilots could hope to pilot an obsolescent zero fighter and survive against the American aviators.
author: Grande Artiste

text: Everybody on here complaining about the CGI or comparing it to Pearl Harbor (even though it's not by the same people), but say nothing about what an amazing story Midway was and still is. Midway and Guadalcanal turned the tide for us in the Pacific. The men who went against Japanese AA fire, more experienced pilots, sailors, and superior fighters brought the US from the brink in the Pacific. Despite losing many planes, we still managed to sink or knock out all 4 of the Japanese carriers, effectively crippling their carrier fleet for the rest of the war. So, who cares if the CGI isn't the best?

text: Horrible. Atrocious. 0:26 Zero fighters armed with 20mm cannons and 7.7mm MGs are going to fly BETWEEN the battleships. Why? To get shot down more easily? 0:39 "Sorry Adm. Nagumo, since I failed to get shot down by flying between the American battleships I chose to get decapitated by a telephone wire."  1:35 That actually happened, but the aircraft is wrong. On 1 February 1942 USS Enterprise was on a raiding mission against the Marshall Islands when a flight of five Mitsubishi G4M bombers attacked. (The movie shows them incorrectly to be G3M Nells.) All their bombs missed and several "Bettys" were hit by Enterprise's AA gunfire. One wounded G4M turned back and made a suicide dive toward the American carrier. Seeing the danger Aviation Machinist Mate 3rd Class Bruno Peter Gaido manned the rear seat gun position of a parked SBD Dauntless and opened fire on the enemy plane. His shooting caused the "Betty" to go out of control and miss the carrier, however, its wing sliced right through the fuselage of the SBD manned by AMM3 Gaido. Rear-Admiral Wm. Halsey personally promoted Gaido for his courage and decisive action. Months later during the Battle of Midway (4 June 1942), Bruno Gaido served as the radioman-gunner of an SBD flown by Ensign Frank O'Flaherty which participated in the attack which fatally incinerated three Japanese aircraft carriers. While returning from the mission O'Flaherty and Gaido were forced to ditch their plane for lack of fuel. Both men escaped the sinking plane and got into a liferaft only to be captured by a Japanese destroy. After interrogation and torture, both men were murdered by their captors by being thrown overboard with weights chained to their legs.

text: I'm no historian, but I do think not a lot of people appreciate history these days and that makes me sad. And it's partly because of films like this, which just make me angry. While I can understand the attempt to make it more interesting, that does not mean adding more explosions, inane dialogue, horrendous CGI, and blatant impossibilities. What directors fail to understand is that the history itself is entertaining enough! It had enough joys, sorrows, drama, and action for a whole generation of people without being mutilated to try and make it cool!   A short list of amazing true events that will probably never feature in this travesty:   -Yorktown came into Pearl Harbor just before the battle heavily damaged from the previous engagement in the Coral Sea and they worked day and night to get her repaired and underway in two days when the original repair time was months. -During the Japanese attack on Midway, the US Marine contingent performed the daily flag-raising ceremony while bombs were exploding everywhere. (See the original Battle of Midway film, taken from footage captured by the on-site journalist who was, by the way, wounded by shrapnel while filming a hangar exploding.) -After the Yorktown was abandoned due to multiple torpedo and bomb hits, a sailor with his guts torn up by shrapnel, forgotten in sickbay, somehow climbed three decks up, across the severely slanting deck, and fired a machine gun burst at a nearby destroyer to get their attention. When men arrived, he told them there was another wounded man down in sickbay. This sailor later died of his injuries, but he saved the life of his comrade, who had a fractured skull but eventually recovered. -When one of the Japanese carriers was being abandoned, the crew determined to save their captain from going down with the ship in spite of himself and sent a Navy wrestling champion to bring him down off the bridge. The sailor came up, saluted, and informed his captain that they were waiting for him. After receiving no reply, he advanced to pick him up but the captain turned around and the look on his face stopped the sailor in his tracks. The sailor then saluted again and left, tears in his eyes, hearing his captain softly singing the Japanese national anthem of the time.   See? Real human drama, heroism, stupidity, cowardice, glory, ignominy, it's all there. Don't try and make it larger than life. Let the story tell itself and tell it with practical, no-nonsense effects as much as possible. (We don't have any period aircraft carriers left, so CGI in the distance shots is unavoidable, but for close-ups, please, none of that.) Sorry. Had to rant about this mess. Anyone who's interested in hearing the whole story can find a good telling of it in the book Miracle at Midway, or hop over to Montemayor's covering of the first part of the fight here on Youtube for an excellent summary.

text: I don't think a Japanese victory at Midway would have led to the "burning" of San Diego, Los Angeles, Seattle, etc. The Japanese plan was to extend their defensive perimeter to Midway Island (to prevent bombing attacks against the Home Islands like the Doolittle Raid) and to deliver another crippling blow to the U.S. Navy, forcing Washington to consider making peace in the Pacific. The intention was never to "own the West Coast" and the stakes they are trying to set are unrealistically high.

text: "If we lose, the Japanese own the West Coast" except, no, the Japanese never, *ever*, stood a chance of winning the war in such a total manner. The best they could have done with a decisive victory at Midway is prolong the war for another two or three years, during which time they'd basically be hoping to capture as much of the west pacific as they could and then get a treaty with the US. The American industrial machine would have outpaced the Japanese regardless of if they lost every single ship at Midway.

text: Those interested in reading a Japanese pilot's account of the Battle of Midway should read 'The Miraculous Torpedo Squadron' by Juzo Mori on Amazon Kindle. Only recently translated into English, Mori's autobiography gives a vivid account of life in pre-war Japan, training to become a pilot, flying in China, training for and carrying out the attack on Pearl Harbor, his role in the attacks on Wake, Midway and Guadalcanal, and more. A must read for students of the Pacific war.

And of course you‚Äôre going to take a little bit of artistic license in the film, what were you expecting a documentary.I personally love all the YouTube military historians commenting about the paranoia that Americans faced about the possibility of Japanese invasion of the mainland and dismissing it. That paranoia existed weather was based in fact or not it was still there. Trying to dismiss peoples opinions from that time period is intellectually disingenuous and lazy. There is a fun movie called 1941 which is a parity. However it does display the insanity of paranoia happening in the United States at that time. text: Something to note about Pearl Harbor was that, while they used a lot of CGI on the aircraft, they used real planes when they needed high-fidelity.  They had actual P-40's and Zeroes, along with some Texan trainers that had been dressed up like Japanese bombers.  That way, our brains had that point of reference for the planes, then just didn't blink when we saw the CGI ones in the heat of the moment.  This is all CGI all the time, which confuses me a bit.  None of these classes of plane have gone anywhere.  Sure, they might not be able to get a flying Val or those modified Texans, but those Zeroes are still around (in fact the exact same planes!) and we've got flyable Dauntlesses around.  They don't need to use them for combat scenes, just have them around for work-a-day purposes to help smooth the illusion.  Or, hell, maybe just don't get that close to the models if they're that bad.  Beyond that, what these planes are doing just makes no sense.  There are resources with very basic information on these planes and their capabilities; no you don't need to be an expert in WWII air combat to know that a B5N "Kate" doesn't have forward firing guns.  Also, why the hell are they so low all the time?  I know they get low on strafing runs, but not that low!  Not "I'm scraping my balls on the radio masts" low, at least not most of the time.  And the massive formation of bombers flying at maybe five hundred feet off the deck is just silly.  I get that concessions need to be made for movies, but this isn't that.  This is taking history and hardcoring it up twelve notches because "we gotta have our pwetty explosions."  I do hope I'm just overreacting, I really am, but this looks like it's gonna be a second Pearl Harbor.  (And before anyone jumps on me, no Pearl Harbor isn't a good movie.  I could rant and rave about the sins of that movie for the better part of a day.  However, the visual effects were actually done with some care.  Sure, it's overdone explosion fodder, because Michael Bay, but some of it would be technically impressive even today, like that rolling battleship scene.)

Early war the japanese fielded better planes than the US.  The US fielded older obsolete planes from the 20's and 30's.   3. text: They had such a great opportunity to portray the battle, the men, and the moment in history in such a way that technology and our vast amounts of knowledge about the battle could allow.  But what we got was the cinematic equivalent of outdated torpedo planes making an attack run on enemy ships without air cover and the bravery required to do so.  Sometimes portraying history and those involved doesn't require over acting, gratuitous campy special effects, and cheesy lines.  My heart pounds harder watching/listening to a solid documentary or info-video on youtube about how this battle played out than any movies like this could do.  I am just disappointed.

text: I saw this movie yesterday ..1st of all let me say that I am so glad that a filmmaker felt the need to retell this great story.. However I feel that it fell short.. It told the story in broad strokes with not nearly enough detail to the battle. I felt it spent  unnecessary amount of time on the fate of dolittle and the Chinese people... The movie is called midway not 30 seconds over Tokyo... It never showed the counter attack on the Yorktown.  I am more than  familiar with the battle of midway and that's the only reason I was able to understand the what was going on throughout the film.. For anyone who was trying to understand or learn about the battle of midway this is not the movie to see.. The original from 1976 did a superior job  Of detailing the battle and conveyed how desperate the search for the carriers was...  In the original movie  They use a lot of war more footage and gun camera footage.. However I did not feel I was watching in Marvel comic.
